<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pseudotsuga macrocarpa </i>is a conifer that reaches 30 (-50) m in height and 700 years of age. Plants begin producing cones at about 20 years of age. Heavy seed crops are rare. Most seeds fall under the parent tree, but wind, rodents, and birds further disperse seeds. Seeds germinate on bare mineral soil and litter, but seedling mortality occurs on litter from damping-off fungi. Seedlings are shade tolerant and can grow under shrub and tree canopies. Plants can penetrate shrub or tree canopies after decades of growth (Howard 1992h, McDonald 1990a). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pseudotsuga macrocarpa </i>favors sites with topography that impedes a fire’s momentum and intensity. Stands usually lack well-developed understory or litter layers, unless they are regenerating from a burn, where shrubs are abundant. Stands are often monospecific; however, some contain a lower tier of <i>Quercus chrysolepis. </i>The first edition recognized a separate <i>Pseudotsuga macrocarpa-Quercus chrysolepis </i>series, but the variance in stand structure does not warrant two alliances. Stands often mingle with stands of many chaparral alliances (Minnich 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
