    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262A). The northernmost stands are in the eastern Sierra Madre Mountains in the extreme southeastern portion of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322A). Stands are mapped along the southern boundary of this subsection, at the edge of the Transverse Ranges (Calveg 2008).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261F). Isolated stands exist north and west of Frazier Park in the San Emigdio Mountains along north facing slopes and draws (Calveg 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261B). Stands exist sporadically in the section on north facing slopes and canyons, including along Santa Paula Ridge, Santa Susana Mountains, and Santa Ana Mountains (Calveg 2010).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262B). Stands in the Transverse Ranges, including those in Cleghorn Canyon cRNA, Fern Canyon and Millard Canyon RNAs (Cheng 2004), in the Peninsular Ranges at Falls Canyon RNA (Sproul 1981, see Cheng 2004), Rouse Ridge in San Bernardino NF and Agua Tibia Mountain in Cleveland NF (Klein and Evens 2005), as well as more generally in the section (McDonald and Littrell 1976, Minnich 1976, 1980a, 1982, Minnich and Everett 2001) help to describe the alliance. The southernmost occur in the Volcan Mountain-Banner Grade vicinity of San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005). Many stands have suffered crown fires in the past decade (Minnich 1999, Evens and San 2005, Kauffmann et al. 2017).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Low-elevation stands were logged heavily during the settlement period (Keeley 2007). Elevated ozone exposure due to air pollution has reduced tree vigor (Arbaugh et al. 1999). Stands in the San Bernardino and eastern San Gabriel mountains have experienced extensive stand replacement burns, most during extreme weather (Minnich 1999). Individual trees and stands that survive fires act as seed sources during fire-free intervals, so local populations can contract and expand during differing fire regimes (Keeley 2007). Short fire return intervals (< 70 years) are a threat in local populations as frequent fires convert stands to chaparral. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
